title: Four Corners in Lenexa  Standing Rally
description: As citizens, we can‚Äôt let the policies and actions of the Federal Government and unelected billionaires be normalized, but we can only stop what‚Äôs going on by coming together.  A STANDING RALLY  will draw attention to the situation, encouraging our neighbors to join with us. We will rally every Saturday morning from 11 AM ‚Äì 12 PM.  Stay for the full hour or come by when and for how long you can. We will peacefully line the sidewalk on all four corners of 87th Parkway and Maurer Road,  holding signs on issues that are most meaningful to us or just simply standing in support of our neighbors and our country.  If sitting is more comfortable for you, you are very welcome to bring mobility or lawn chairs!! There is room for everyone!
accessibility_notes:
Here are a couple of notes on logistics.
Please be especially mindful of parking.  For example, if you live relatively nearby, please consider walking.  If you drive, there is street parking on the residential streets to the north and also a bit further on the south.  About ¬Ω mile down on the west, there is a large civic campus garage at 17201 W 87th St. Pkwy.  In addition, on the SE, SW, and NW sides of the intersection, there are restaurants and shops with big, but commercially owned parking lots meant for customers.  (Please note that if you become a customer, it‚Äôs fine to bring snacks to the rally that you have bought, but please take any empty snack containers back home with you, when you leave. In any case, no matter which direction you are coming from, if it is possible, please try to park before you reach the intersection to save on congestion and choose a spot as far away as you feel comfortable walking from, leaving closer spots to those who can‚Äôt walk as far.
The rally will start on the SE corner, but as more folks arrive, we will disperse to the SW, NW, and NE corners, as well.   If you cross from one side to another, please pay particular attention to cars turning right as you cross! 
 Participants should bring their own signs (if they want to hold them).  Note that sticks supporting the signs can‚Äôt be pointed at either end.  Also, in designing content for the signs, please remember that children will be present.  
Please stand only along the sidewalks parallel to the street and not on the grass.  However, also be sure to allow pedestrian access to the sidewalk and businesses.   We are not expecting issues, but keep in mind that a core principle behind our events is a commitment to nonviolent action.  Remember to de-escalate any potential confrontation with someone,  who disagrees with you. And of course, follow directions from our excellent Lenexa police, if asked.
We will not have speakers. The plan will simply be to hold the signs we have made and wave, if that feels right.  We expect that a lot of passing cars will honk back in approval! 
Finally, please note that all our organizers will be wearing lanyards with badges reading  ‚ÄúStanding Rally Corner Captain or ‚ÄúStanding Rally Media/City Liaison‚Äù.  If you see other folks with ‚ÄúPress‚Äù marked on their clothing or who are giving direction to you, know that they are not part of Four Corners and are not endorsed or vetted by us.
See you soon.  Let‚Äôs show our neighbors ‚Äúwhat Democracy Looks Like‚Äù!!
P.S.  If you want to post an inspiring (!) story about your experience, please add #FourCornersinLenexa to your post!

title: Indivisible Red & Rural Caucus May Call
description:
What does Pride mean to you? What do you think it means and looks like for your small or rural community? 

Now take what you said, and think about it from a different angle. What does Pride mean to the LGBTQIA+ community who lives in red, rural or small town America? Right now, Pride is one of the last bastions of all positive visibility for people who identify as LGBTQIA+, and more than ever before this pride is under attack. 

From the Trump administration on day one stating that there are only two sexes and genders, to the right wing attacks against all Transgender individuals (children and adults alike), people in our communities are scared. They feel as though attacks come from every side today and they feel as though their community is at risk. 

Here at the Indivisible Red and Rural Caucus, we know how tough it is to live in red, rural and small town America, and now that we have all defined what community means to us, it's our job to be inclusive and supportive of all communities. June is Pride Month, and we are ready to turn out to support all individuals regardless of whether they are Gay, Lesbian, Transgender, Questioning, Intersex, Asexual and beyond! Join us for our May Red and Rural Caucus where we will learn how to continue rebuilding our communities in small town America by supporting one of the most at risk communities there is in our nation. When we stand together in community and collectively raise our voices, its much harder for fascists to fight us. 

Join us on May 28th for a Pride Themed Red and Rural Caucus Call, and learn how you can be the best Ally all year round, not just during Pride!

They‚Äôll discuss what our organizations are doing to improve the conditions for wildlife throughout this important landscape in partnership with other NGOs, state, and federal agencies. 

You'll also learn how to get involved in various projects. These include a study of wildlife-traffic interactions that will inform an effort to install wildlife-crossing structures along Arizona Highway 82, as well as volunteer trips to close old roads in the Coronado National Forest, document and improve water sources, and more.

title: Food Pantry Collection at Labor's Stop the Billionaires Rally
description:
The Beaver County Democratic Committee is proud to stand with our allies at the Beaver-Lawrence Central Labor Council to show solidarity with the Unions challenging the Trump administration's dismantling of rights to organize and to protest the firing of federal workers.

In conjunction with the rally, we are collecting non-perishable food to distribute to the Little Free Food Pantries across Beaver County. Please join us as we stand with Labor, and if you are able, please bring a donation.

Items most needed for the pantries are: pasta, pasta sauce (plastic bottles only), mac and cheese, ramen noodles, canned or pouched meats (tuna, salmon, chicken, etc.), peanut butter and jelly, canned soups, chili, and stews, shampoo/conditioner, soap, toothpaste, and deodorant.

title: Harrison County Democratic Party Convention
description:
Every four years, Kentucky Democrats gather to organize and refresh our volunteer efforts to promote democracy, economic justice and establish a strong support team for our Democratic candidates across Harrison County and the entire state.

Reorg ("reorganization") is when we elect new leadership of the Harrison County Democratic Party and establish our 20-member  county executive committee. During this process, we also elect delegates to the state convention.

Do you want to become an active volunteer? Do you want to help shape the party and plan its activities and programming? Do you want to get involved in candidate recruitment, training and fundraising?

description: SCDC has voted to send over 9000 mail in ballot applications to people that voted in 2024, but not 2023.  This will help to get out the vote for our local candidates this year.
